bioghist.head: Biographical note
bioghist.p: Jane Gentry Vance was born on February 9, 1941 to Charles Blanding Gentry and Dixie Walker Gentry and grew up on the family farm in Athens, Fayette County, Kentucky. She attended Tates Creek High School in Lexington before matriculating to Hollins College in Virginia from 1959-1963. At Hollins College she studied under the founder of Hollins' Creative Writing Program, Louis D. Rubin, and he remained her mentor and friend until his death in 2013. Vance also attended Brandeis University (M.A.), and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill (Ph.D.). In 1971, she returned to live in the Lexington, Kentucky area and began teaching at Georgetown College and then at the University Of Kentucky. She taught classes for UK's Department of English and Honors Program until her retirement after forty years. In addition to her role as professor, Vance led many writing workshops around the country, wrote reviews for journals and newspapers, published articles, and participated in church events at St. John's Episcopal Church in Versailles, Kentucky. She published two collections of her poetry, A Garden in Kentucky (Louisiana State University Press, 1996) and Portrait of an Artist as a White Pig (Louisiana State University Press, 2006). Jane Gentry Vance served as Kentucky Poet Laureate from 2007-2008, a position which required her to speak and give readings throughout the commonwealth nearly everyday.

Vance had an interest in her family genealogy and the region, which led her to write with a fellow Athenian, Babe Lamb, a history of Athens, Kentucky printed in 1986. Vance inherited photographs and keepsakes of her paternal grandmother's sister, Tommie House Kane, 1886-1980, the first female licensed pilot in Kentucky and author. Jane Gentry Vance had two daughters, Lucy and Susannah, and raised them in Versailles, Kentucky. Vance died from cancer on October 2, 2014.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Jane Gentry Vance papers (dated 1890-2015, undated; 21.25 cubic feet; 29 boxes) comprise the correspondence, event records, family and history research, manuscripts, photographs, publications and teacher files of Kentucky Poet Laureate and University of Kentucky Lewis Honors College professor, Jane Gentry Vance. A significant portion of the collection contains contact and promotional content from special events, interviews, readings, and workshops Vance attended and gave throughout the commonwealth as Kentucky Poet Laureate during 2007-2008. Another large portion of the collection includes manuscripts, drafts, revisions, and publications of articles, poems, and reviews authored by Vance. Also present are handouts, letters, papers, notes, and syllabi from Vance's years as a student, as well as her long career as a professor. While most of the collection represents her life as an author and teacher, it also includes personal letters, journals, and family keepsakes. Of note is a scrapbook containing photographs from the beginning of the twentieth century of Vance's aunt, Tommie House Kane's life as an artist in Lexington and Athens, Kentucky.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Collection is open to researchers by appointment.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The physical rights to the materials in this collection are held by the University of Kentucky Special Collections Research Center.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Audiovisual series (1890-2011, undated) comprises photographs, computer floppy disks, microfilm, audio cassettes, and videos. The photographs primarily contain images of Jane Gentry Vance at events, family pictures, and Athens, Kentucky. Of note is a photo album with photos of Jane's aunt, Tommie House Kane, Kentucky's first female pilot, author from the 1920's.The 3½-inch floppy disks and microfilm primarily contain University English honors class handouts, records, and the department's creative writing journal. The audio cassettes and video tapings of interviews, presentations, and poetry readings. Also included are computer disks of Vance's 1989 paper with Louis Rubin and a DVD film of Hollins University tribute to Louis Rubin in 2011.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Athens history and family genealogy series (1890-2013, undated) contains correspondence, research for and drafts of A Short History of Athens, Kentucky and Looking Back at Athens, two books written by Vance with William M. Lamb during the 1980's. The series also includes genealogical research conducted by Vance of her family, primarily farmers who lived in Athens, Kentucky.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Education series (1960-2014, undated) contains notes, readings, papers, and records from Jane Gentry Vance's time as a student from high school through to her doctoral degree and in English. Also included are letters and papers edited by or collaborated with Vance's lifelong mentor, professor and author, Louis D. Rubin.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Events, readings, and workshops series (1961-2013, undated) comprises fliers, correspondence, and other ephemera from engagements Jane Gentry Vance attended, led, and/or participated in. The majority of the series consists of materials related to readings Vance gave as Kentucky poet laureate to schools, libraries, clubs, and other social gatherings during 2007-2008. Also included are promotional events for published works like book signings, conferences, the Kentucky Book Fair.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Manuscripts and other works (1958-2011, undated) comprises books and poems by Jane Gentry Vance's contemporaries, as well as the drafts, revisions, printings of books, reviews, papers, and many poems by Vance. The series contains the drafts for Vance's two books, a collection of poems, A Garden in Kentucky (1995) and Portrait of the Artist as a White Pig (2006). Also included is correspondence with editing boards and publishers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Personal papers series (1941-2015, undated) contains Jane Gentry Vance's biography, correspondence, clippings, day planners, family records, notes, and other non-professional documents. The bulk of the series includes correspondence between family and friends. Notably, many of the letters are from other Kentucky writers and artists, like Bobbie Ann Mason, George Ella Lyon, and Nikky Finney.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Publicity and news clippings series (1936-2013, undated) primarily consists of interviews with Jane Gentry Vance for radio, television, magazines, journals, and newspapers. The series also includes newspaper and magazine clippings of topics Vance researched like Kentucky history and other writers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Teaching records series (1970-2013, undated) comprises appointment books, handouts, student work, syllabi, and other teaching aids of Jane Gentry Vance's position as an English professor at the University of Kentucky Lewis Honors College from 1972-2013. The series also includes departmental and tenure records. A large portion of the series includes student documents and published editions of Jar: a creative arts journal published by honors program students in a class taught by Vance.
